    "cheatsheetContent": "Solve the implication by trying syntax first and semantics second.\nEquation 1:\n{{ equation1 }}\nEquation 2:\n{{ equation2 }}\n\nReasoning order:\n- First try a direct syntactic derivation from Equation 1 to Equation 2.\n- If that fails, switch to semantic separation and look for a witness where Equation 1 holds but Equation 2 fails.\n- Use `TRUE` only with an explicit derivation.\n- Use `FALSE` only with a concrete witness.\n\nRequired output:\nVERDICT: TRUE or FALSE\nREASONING: state whether syntax succeeded or semantics separated the equations\nPROOF:\nfill only when VERDICT is TRUE\nCOUNTEREXAMPLE:\nfill only when VERDICT is FALSE\n\nOutput rules:\n- Plain text only.\n- No extra headings or notes.\n- `VERDICT:` must be exactly `TRUE` or `FALSE`.\n- `REASONING:` must always be filled.\n- If `VERDICT: TRUE`, `PROOF:` must be non-empty and `COUNTEREXAMPLE:` empty.\n- If `VERDICT: FALSE`, `COUNTEREXAMPLE:` must be non-empty and `PROOF:` empty.",
